`crates/ctx-cage/src/bin/` holds the two executable entry points that
front the sandboxed-agent lifecycle: `ctx_cage.rs` (the generic containment
host) and `ctx_run.rs` (the billed, project-facing agent-session launcher),
plus `ctx_run/` which supplies `ctx_run.rs`'s config-resolution and
secrets-loading helpers.

Both binaries gate paid API usage behind explicit opt-in — `ctx_cage.rs`
via `--allow-spend`/`CTX_CAGE_ALLOW_SPEND`, `ctx_run.rs` via its y/N prompt
(or `--allow-dirty`-style flags) — and both read local, permission-checked
env files (`.cagevars`, `~/.config/ctx/env`) for secrets that must never
reach the sandboxed subprocess's environment beyond the specific variables
each caller intends to forward. `ctx_run.rs` builds its `Resolved` config
via `ctx_run::resolve`, keeping that separation (`env_file.rs`'s secrets
stay confined to the post-run summarizer, never merged into `extra_env`)
which both binaries' host-side logic depends on.

`ctx_cage.rs` is the general-purpose orchestrator: it resolves sibling
tool binaries, resolves mode, and hands off to `lifecycle::execute()`, with
uniform host-side error handling (exit 1, stderr) across all failure paths.
`ctx_run.rs` is a higher-level, domain-specific wrapper around the same
lifecycle, adding session-completion behavior (optional `ctx-scan --update`
refresh with hardcoded models) that `ctx_cage.rs` has no equivalent for.
Both ultimately produce/consume `CageError` and a `lifecycle::Resolved`.